1. newSingleThreadExecutor & newFixedThreadPool(n)

Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);
// corePoolSize = 4, maxPoolSize = 4

Strategy: Lazy, but only up to corePoolSize
execute(T1) → Thread-1 created
execute(T2) → Thread-2 created
execute(T3) → Thread-3 created
execute(T4) → Thread-4 created
execute(T5) → all 4 threads busy → T5 goes into queue, NO new thread
execute(T6) → T6 goes into queue, NO new thread

- Threads are created one per task until corePoolSize is reached
- After that, queue fills up, threads are never destroyed (they live forever waiting)

2. newCachedThreadPool

Executors.newCachedThreadPool();
// corePoolSize = 0, maxPoolSize = Integer.MAX_VALUE, queue = SynchronousQueue

Strategy: Create a new thread for EVERY task if no idle thread exists
execute(T1) → Thread-1 created (no idle thread available)
execute(T2) → Thread-2 created (Thread-1 is busy)
execute(T3) → Thread-3 created (all busy)
// ... 1 minute later, all tasks done
execute(T4) → Thread-1 reused (was idle, not yet expired)

- Uses a SynchronousQueue — zero capacity, tasks are handed off directly to a thread
- Idle threads are destroyed after 60 seconds — pool shrinks back to 0
- Can spin up unlimited threads — dangerous under high load (OutOfMemoryError)

3. newScheduledThreadPool(n)

Executors.newScheduledThreadPool(2);
// corePoolSize = n, maxPoolSize = Integer.MAX_VALUE, queue = DelayedWorkQueue

Strategy: Same lazy creation as Fixed, but uses a priority queue sorted by execution time
schedule(T1, delay=5s) → goes into DelayedWorkQueue
schedule(T2, delay=2s) → goes into DelayedWorkQueue
// T2 runs first because it has shorter delay

- Thread creation is same as Fixed — lazy up to corePoolSize
- The difference is the queue is a min-heap sorted by scheduled time, not FIFO
- A thread sleeps inside the queue until the next task's delay expires

4. newWorkStealingPool

Executors.newWorkStealingPool();
// Uses ForkJoinPool internally, NOT ThreadPoolExecutor

Strategy: Completely different — creates ALL threads upfront
// Default: parallelism = Runtime.getRuntime().availableProcessors()
// e.g., on an 8-core machine → 8 threads created immediately at pool creation

- This is the only pool that creates threads eagerly (not lazily)
- Each thread has its own deque (double-ended queue) of tasks
- If Thread-1 finishes its tasks, it steals from the tail of Thread-2's deque
- Uses daemon threads — JVM can exit even if tasks are pending (unlike all others)


